## Creating Pull Requests

### Size Guidelines
- ✅ Keep PRs small and focused
- ✅ Aim for around 100 lines of change
- ❌ Avoid PRs larger than 1000 lines
- ✅ Split large changes into multiple PRs

### Best Practices
- ✅ Make one self-contained change per PR
- ✅ Include related test code
- ✅ Ensure system works after each PR
- ✅ Keep PRs independent when possible
- ✅ Include all necessary context

## Commit Messages

### Conventional Commits Format
```
<type>[optional scope]: <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

### Types
- `feat`: New feature
- `fix`: Bug fix
- `docs`: Documentation changes
- `style`: Code style changes
- `refactor`: Code refactoring
- `perf`: Performance improvements
- `test`: Adding/updating tests
- `build`: Build system changes
- `ci`: CI configuration changes
- `chore`: Other changes

### Examples
```bash
feat(auth): add OAuth2 login support
fix(api): handle null response in user endpoint
docs(readme): update installation instructions
```

## PR Description

### First Line
- ✅ Write a short, focused summary
- ✅ Use imperative mood
- ✅ Keep it under 72 characters
- ✅ Make it standalone

### Body
- ✅ Explain what and why
- ✅ Include context and background
- ✅ Mention any trade-offs
- ✅ Reference related issues/PRs
- ✅ Include relevant metrics/data

### Examples

#### Good Example
```
Add rate limiting to API endpoints

Implement rate limiting to prevent abuse of our API endpoints. This change:
- Adds rate limiting middleware
- Configures limits based on user tier
- Includes monitoring and alerts
- Updates documentation

Fixes #123
```

#### Bad Example
```
Fix bug
```

## Code Review Process

### Review Speed
- ✅ Respond to PRs within 24 hours
- ✅ Prioritize small PRs
- ✅ Block on blocking issues only
- ✅ Use "LGTM" for simple approvals

### Review Focus
1. Code Health
   - Design
   - Functionality
   - Complexity
   - Testing
   - Naming
   - Comments

2. Security
   - Input validation
   - Authentication
   - Authorization
   - Data handling

3. Performance
   - Algorithm efficiency
   - Resource usage
   - Scalability

## Reviewer Guidelines

### Review Steps
1. Look at the big picture
2. Look for potential issues
3. Look at the details
4. Look for tests
5. Look for documentation

### Comment Guidelines
- ✅ Be constructive and helpful
- ✅ Explain reasoning
- ✅ Accept author's style
- ✅ Distinguish between preferences and requirements
- ✅ Avoid "nit" comments

### Navigation Tips
- ✅ Start with a high-level review
- ✅ Look at tests first
- ✅ Review related files
- ✅ Check for consistency

## Author Guidelines

### Responding to Reviews
- ✅ Thank reviewers
- ✅ Address all comments
- ✅ Explain if disagreeing
- ✅ Push back when appropriate
- ✅ Iterate until resolved

### Handling Pushback
- ✅ Stay professional
- ✅ Explain reasoning
- ✅ Provide data when possible
- ✅ Accept feedback when valid
- ✅ Escalate if needed

### Best Practices
- ✅ Keep PRs up to date
- ✅ Respond promptly
- ✅ Be open to feedback
- ✅ Maintain good communication
- ✅ Follow up on resolved issues